<HEADLINE> Iran Accuses U.S. of Harassing Ships in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bandar Abbas (Iran), July 3 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian Foreign
Ministry official on Saturday accused the United States of
harassing Iranian and foreign ships in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is still creating problems for navigation in the
Persian Gulf under the pretext checking food dispatches to
Iraq, Mohammad Hussein Forouqi, an official in charge of legal
affairs, said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the sidelines of a ceremony to mark the 11th
anniversary of the downing of an Iranian passenger plane by
a U.S. warship in the Gulf, Forouqi said that the cases of U.S.
harassment have been reported to the United Nations and Iran
would follow up the matter.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. by no means is allowed to check or inspect vessels in
the Persian Gulf and the U.N. has not permitted it to do so, he
said, stressing that the continued U.S. presence in the Gulf is
creating problems for the regional countries.
</P>
<P>
Iran has repeatedly warned that the U.S. military presence
in the Gulf region was the real threat to the regional security
and stability. It called for regional cooperation to maintain
security and stability without foreign intervention.
</P>
<P>
An Iranian passenger plane, en route from Bandar Abbas, the
capital of Iran's southern Hormozgan province to Dubai, the
United Arab Emirates, was shot down on July 3 1988 by two
missiles fired by the U.S. warship Vincennes in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
All the 290 passengers and crew members, including 160 men,
73 women and 57 children, were killed in the incident.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Managing Director of the Iranian
flag carrier (Iran Air) Ahmad Reza Kazemi asked the U.S.
to make an official apology to the Iranian nation, government
and families of the victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
