<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects GCC Call over Disputed Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Saturday rejected the
call by foreign ministers of the members states of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) for efforts to solve the territorial
dispute between Iran and the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi expressed
dissatisfaction with the statement of the GCC foreign ministerial
meeting concluded in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Termed the statement as "partial and unacceptable," Asefi said
that the position adopted by the GCC foreign ministers is against
Iran's territorial integrity, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the three islands of Abu Musa, the Greater
and Lesser Tunbs belong to Iran and are an integral part of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Iran is prepared to remove the misunderstandings with the
UAE through direct negotiations, he added.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia
and the UAE decided on Saturday to form an ad hoc committee to
help resolve the territorial dispute between the UAE and Iran over
the three islands at the mouth of the strategic Hormoz Strait.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which comprises Oman, Qatar and Saudi Arabia,
will devise a mechanism to discuss the UAE-Iranian dispute over
three Gulf Islands, according to the final statement issued at the
end of the GCC ministerial council meeting held in the Saudi Red
Sea port city of Jeddah.
</P>
<P>
Iran took over the islands in 1971 soon after the British
colonialist forces withdrew from the region. However, both Tehran
and Abu Dhabi claimed full sovereignty over the islands.
</P>
<P>
Iran has repeatedly called for mutual talks to remove
"misunderstanding" between the two countries, but the UAE has
called for international arbitration to solve the dispute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
