<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Team Visits Destroyed Iraqi Vaccine Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 3 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations delegation visited
on Saturday a livestock vaccine plant in Baghdad, Iraq, which was
destroyed by U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, led by Executive Director of the U.N. Program
for Iraq Benon Sevan, was briefed on the situation of the foot and
mouth disease (FMD) vaccine plant destroyed in 1996 by the
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Sevan said the U.N. would send a technical team later this
month to Iraq to check this plant and its laboratories and
evaluate the possibility of rehabilitating it.
</P>
<P>
Livestock husbandry in Iraq and its neighboring countries are
now suffering heavily from the outbreak of FMD.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi media have reported that some 1.5 million heads of Iraqi
cattle and sheep have died of FMD so far this year.
</P>
<P>
During the 1970s Iraq set up a strategic vaccination project
capable of producing 12 million doses annually for preventing
animal diseases.
</P>
<P>
The project was suspended due to the 1991 Gulf War and most of
its production and diagnosis equipment were destroyed in 1996 by
UNSCOM on the ground that they are of dual use.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, when FMD became rampant, Iraq sent a letter
to the U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan requesting urgent
supplies of FMD vaccines.
</P>
<P>
Iraq also demanded U.N. compensation for the loss of its
citizens caused by the spread of FMD among livestock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
