<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Demands U.S. Apology for Downing Passenger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bandar Abbas (Iran), July 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Saturday once
again asked the United States to make an official apology to the
Iranian government and nation for shooting down an Iranian
passenger plane in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Managing Director of the
Iranian flag carrier (Iran Air) Ahmad Reza Kazemi said that so far
the U.S. only expressed regret over the downing of the Iranian
airbus plane over the Gulf before the end of Iran-Iraq war.
</P>
<P>
Although the U.S. has paid the "minimum compensations" to Iran
Air and the families of the victim, "but it is not enough, the
U.S. must make an official apology to the Iranian nation,
government and families of the victims," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian passenger plane, en route from Bandar Abbas, the
capital of Iran's southern Hormozgan province to Dubai, the United
Arab Emirates, was shot down on July 3 1988 by two missiles fired
by the U.S. warship Vincennes in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
All the 290 passengers and crew members, including 160 men,
73 women and 57 children, were killed in the incident.
</P>
<P>
Kazemi said that the U.S. administration not only failed to
punish those responsible for the crime, but it awarded the
warship's captain.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the impact of the issue on Tehran-Washington ties,
he said that surely the case was a hurdle for the relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Had the U.S. made official apology to Iran, at least it
removed one of the obstacles on the way of Tehran-Washington
ties, he said.
</P>
<P>
Before the press conference, officials from Iran Air, military
forces and representatives of victims' families attended a
ceremony on a vessel at the site of the incident in the Persian
Gulf, showering flowers to commemorate the victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
