<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC Urges New Israeli Government to Resume Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) foreign ministers on Saturday called on Israel's new
government to resume stalled peace talks with Arabs on all tracks.
</P>
<P>
The final communique issued after a brief closed-door meeting
of the foreign ministers in the western Saudi city of Jeddah said
that Israel must return the Arab lands in line with related United
Nations resolutions, the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Jerusalem must also be the capital of an
independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The GCC top diplomats condemned the recent Israeli air raids
against Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel, on June 24 and 25, launched intensive air strikes
against Lebanese civilian targets, killing eight people and
wounding more than 60 others.
</P>
<P>
The statement urged the international community to pressure
Israel into respecting the 1996 April understanding and put an
end to Israeli aggression.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 understanding bans Israel and the anti-Israel Lebanese
resistance forces from launching attacks against or from civilian
targets.
</P>
<P>
The GCC foreign ministers called on Israeli Prime
Minister-elect Ehud Barak to resume "serious negotiations" with
the Arabs and honor the commitments of the former governments.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance established
in 1981, comprises Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and
the UAE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
