<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgian Farmers To Protest On Food Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Belgian farmers are preparing for
a demonstration here in the capital of Belgium on Sunday to
protest against the government's handling of the crisis over
dioxin-contaminated food.
</P>
<P>
"It is imperative that our politicians take measures to support
this sector, which has been seriously weakened by the exceptional
and sudden dramatic circumstances," organizers of the farmers'
protest said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Organizers expect between 10,000 and 15,000 demonstrators but
it could be more," Brussels mayor Francois-Xavier de Donnea told
reporters on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Brussels authorities have said all tractors, trucks and
other heavy farm vehicles will be banned from entering the capital
during the march. About 2,700 police would be deployed to ensure
the demonstration went smoothly, the Brussels mayor said.
</P>
<P>
The dioxin-contaminated food crisis is officially estimated to
cost 60 billion Belgian francs (1.54 billion U.S. dollars). The
food crisis started in late May when high level cancer-causing
dioxin was found in home-grown eggs, meat and dairy produce, which
were banned from sales both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian government has so far allocated 6.3 billion francs
(161 million U.S. dollars) to help farmers and businesses hit by
the food scare, which is believed to be Europe's biggest since the
mad cow crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
