<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwaiti voters flocked to
the 190 polling stations across the country Saturday morning to
elect their ninth National Assembly (parliament) since 1963.
</P>
<P>
The eighth National Assembly was constitutionally dissolved by
Emir Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah in March 1998, following a deadlock
in relations between the parliament and government.
(BC-Kuwait-Polls)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) foreign
ministers decided on Saturday to form an ad hoc committee to
tackle the territorial dispute between the United Arab Emirates
(UAE) and Iran.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which comprises Oman, Qatar and Saudi Arabia,
will devise a mechanism to discuss the UAE-Iranian dispute over
three Gulf Islands, said the final communique issued after a brief
meeting of the GCC ministerial council held in the Saudi Red Sea
port city of Jeddah.
(BC-GCC-FMs-Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- A United Nations delegation visited on Saturday a
livestock vaccine plant in Baghdad, Iraq, which was destroyed by
U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, led by Executive Director of the U.N. Program
for Iraq Benon Sevan, was briefed on the situation of the foot and
mouth disease (FMD) vaccine plant destroyed in 1996 by the
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
(BC-Iraq-UN-FMD) 
</P>
</TEXT>
