<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Says Committed to OAU Framework Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia as always remains
committed to the Organization of African Unity (OAU) framework
agreement that requires Eritrea to withdraw its troops from all
occupied Ethiopian territories, the Ethiopian foreign ministry
said here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a statement that Ethiopia had all along
insisted that the OAU framework agreement proposed to peacefully
settle the dispute between the two countries be implemented
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued over one week before the forthcoming
35th OAU summit which will be convened in Algiers on July 12,
1999.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Ethiopia has since the start of the
Ethio- Eritrean conflict worked tirelessly for the peaceful
resolution of the conflict and has accordingly fully supported the
OAU framework agreement from the very beginning.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea, despite its professed acceptance of the framework
agreement, has refused to withdraw its troops from the areas it
occupied since May 6, 1998 and to allow the Ethiopian civil
administration of those areas to be restored fully, the foreign
ministry was quoted by the Ethiopian News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
It is in this light that Ethiopia welcomes the on-going efforts
of Libya and other friendly countries to facilitate the full
implementation of the OAU framework agreement and hopes that these
endeavors will bear fruit, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The conflict between the two Horn of Africa neighbors broke out
on May 6, 1998 over a disputed stretch of their border. Both
Ethiopia and Eritrea have announced to accept the OAU peaceful
proposal, but they haven't so far reached a cease-fire on their
over one-year border conflict and blamed each other for other
side' s launching new attack. The Ethio-Eritrean crisis will be
discussed at the 35th OAU summit next week in Algerian capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
