<HEADLINE> Clinton Agrees to Meet with Sharif over Kashmir Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton has
agreed to meet with Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif on
Sunday to discuss the way for resolving the "dangerous" conflict
with india over long-disputed Kashmir, the White House announced
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A White House official said Sharif had requested the meeting
in a telephone conversation with Clinton. And Clinton then
telephoned Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, who
raised no objections for the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister Sharif requested the meeting given that the
situation in Kashmir is increasingly tense," the official said.
</P>
<P>
And a statement released by the White House press office said
that both leaders agreed "the situation is dangerous and could
escalate if not resolved quickly."
</P>
<P>
The official said Clinton has long been concerned over
developments in the border area and has been conferring with
both sides for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
"We have made our position on the conflict clear," the
official said, adding that Clinton believes that India and
Pakistan should quickly return to direct dialogue.
</P>
<P>
But he said Clinton does not intend to use the meeting with
Sharif as an attempt to mediate the conflict.
</P>
<P>
"We believe this has to be resolved through bilateral
dialogue," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
