<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Graf Calls it Quit on Wimbledon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- World tennis queen Steffi Graf of
Germany brought down the curtain on her glorious Wimbledon career
following her final defeat at the hands of Lindsay Davenport on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The seven-times champion made the announcement after losing 6-4,
7-5 to the American on Centre Court but refused to reveal whether
she was retiring from the game.
</P>
<P>
"I will not be coming back to Wimbledon as a player," the 30-
year-old Graf said. "I'm not talking about whether I will play on
at the moment.
</P>
<P>
"I decided before the match, the result would not have made any
difference."
</P>
<P>
Graf, who won her first Wimbledon title at the All England Club
in 1988, added: "Nothing was going to change my mind.
</P>
<P>
"Right now I feel a little bit sad about everything but I still
feel like a winner going out of this tournament.
</P>
<P>
"It has been a lot of fun but there has to be a certain time
when you move on in your life," she added.
</P>
<P>
After winning the French Open last month for the sixth time,
Graf retired from the Roland Garros tournament. Before the
Wimbledon final, Graf once hinted that it would be "tempting" to
come back to Wimbledon next year if she manages to capture her
eighth title. 
</P>
</TEXT>
