<HEADLINE> Guangxi Bans Leaded Gasoline to Reduce Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region has imposed a ban in its two major cities on producing,
selling and using leaded gasoline.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to reduce pollution caused by vehicle emissions, the
provincial government has decided that the ban is to be carried
out in Nanning, capital of Guangxi and Guilin, a famous tourist
attraction.
</P>
<P>
Nanning has 230,000 motor vehicles, 90 percent of which use
leaded gasoline, one of the city's major pollutants.
</P>
<P>
Now, the 217 gasoline stations in the city are ready to switch
to lead-free products.
</P>
<P>
The provincial environmental protection departments will link
up with technical supervision departments to monitor and penalize
violators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
