<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Restructures Nuclear Industrial System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ratified by the State Council, the CNIG is an extremely large
state-owned enterprise formed on the basis of some enterprises and
units of the original China National Nuclear Corp (CNNC).
</P>
<P>
Directly under the control of the central government, the CNIG
will operate nuclear power stations, nuclear heat-supply reactors,
scientific research reactors, radiation devices and other nuclear
facilities, and will also develop scientific research in fields
related to the nuclear industry.
</P>
<P>
Since China introduced its opening and reform policies 20 years
ago, the country's nuclear industrial administrative system has
experienced two major restructurings: the establishment of the
CNNC to replace the Ministry of Nuclear Industry in 1988 and the
winding up of the Ministry of Energy in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The newly established CNIG is an economic entity which will
operate independently according to market rules. While
guaranteeing military scientific research and production, the
group will focus on the development of nuclear power and the
nuclear fuel industry, and make efforts to develop nuclear
technological applications.
</P>
<P>
The CNIG will restructure and standardize its member
enterprises in accordance with the Corporate Law and gradually set
up a modern corporate system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
