<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Higher Yields And Better Quality of Summer Crops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The current summer harvest in China
has produced higher yields and a better quality of grain thanks to
a new government agricultural policy which was introduced last
year in a bid to improve productivity and output.
</P>
<P>
Since last Autumn, although many areas have suffered from
drought, the country's grain production has remained stable,
according to officials.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that so far in 1999 the summer crops,
mainly wheat, covered about 31 million hectares, over 800,000
hectares less than 1998, but the unit yields have increased and
the entire output may also be higher.
</P>
<P>
The officials attribute it to the expanded acreage of croplands
that are using good quality seeds, now totaling more than two
million hectares; more investment in water-effective irrigation
projects and farm technology, amounting to 25 billion yuan (three
billion US dollars) in the past three years; and greater
popularity of farm machines such as the 80,000 combine harvesters
which were used this summer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990704.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technological Gap Between India, Developed Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Technological gap between India
and developed countries was widening due to many factors,
according to a joint study published on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Administrative Staff College of India (ASCI) in Hyderabad,
1,500 kms south of here, and Union Finance Secretary Vijay Kelkar
said in their study that the gap was reflected by India's poor
investments in research and development, lack of penetration into
high technology areas, weak linkages between research institutions
and the industry and poor performance in patenting.
</P>
<P>
The report appraised the technology development in India
vis-a-vis emerging global scenario, the Press Trust of India (PTI)
reported from Hyderabad where the report was published.
</P>
<P>
With its share in the world trade falling below 0.5 percent,
India would find it difficult to cope with global competition in
the face of stricter intellectual property rights regimes unless
major initiatives were taken to enhance critical technology
capabilities and to strengthen national innovation systems, the
study warned.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Strategic Management of Technology Division in
ASCI, B. Bowonder, proposed that a new national policy of
innovation be focus on commercialization of critical technologies,
collaborative research and development, patenting innovation,
designing new products and necessary linkages for exploiting
innovations in the market.
</P>
<P>
"In the changing global competitive landscape, there is a
world-wide trend to aggressively pursue export markets of high
technology products while India's share in this critical sector
had been very low and no initiative has been taken to reverse this
trend except in software segment," Bowonder told the PTI. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
