<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Davenport Beats Graf in Wimbledon Women's Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- American Lindsay Davenport won her
first Wimbledon title as she powered past Steffi Graf of Germany 6-
4, 7-5 at the women's final on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old American, who returns to the world number one
spot tomorrow after advancing into the final of the championship,
showed no signs of nerves in her first appearance in a Wimbledon
singles final, which was suspended by rain for about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The US Open champion broke Graf's serve in the opening game of
the match as she sent a backhand return down the line and then
managed to hold her own serve in the next game with powerful
serving and dominance at the net.
</P>
<P>
Davenport disputed two decisions by the umpire but nevertheless
managed to maintain her composure and dominated Graf by hemming
her in on the baseline with the length and direction of her
powerful baseline shots.
</P>
<P>
She secured the set on her second set point when French Open
champion Graf, who had just hit a forehand winner, netted a low
backhand.
</P>
<P>
In the second set, after Graf led at 5-4 and Davenport served
the 20th game 30-15, unexpected rain came and stopped the match
for half an hour.
</P>
<P>
After the play was resumed, Davenport, third seed in the
tournament, continued her form and took the game, levelling the
set 5-5.
</P>
<P>
The next game swung the match crucially Davenport's way.
</P>
<P>
The German took a 30-0 lead but a series of errors on the
backhand and forehand saw her held to deuce twice before a Graf
forehand into the net earned Davenport only her second break point
of the match.
</P>
<P>
A superb forehand into the corner left Graf grasping at air and
Davenport was 6-5 ahead.
</P>
<P>
Two aces took her to her first match point, which she wasted
with tame backhand into the net as the pressure of the moment
seemed to get to her.
</P>
<P>
But Graf netted yet another forehand to hand Davenport her
first Wimbledon title. The American turned away and put her hand
to her mouth in her moment of triumph, before the tears started to
flow.
</P>
<P>
"It sounds almost like a dream. I'm in shock, I can't believe I
did it," said Davenport, who has regained the world number one
spot with her Wimbledon success.
</P>
<P>
"What an amazing thing - I'll take the Wimbledon champion any
day over the world number one ranking. I won't forget this - it's
the most beautiful trophy I've ever seen."
</P>
<P>
"I served well and that was the main thing. I only had two
break points and it was pretty amazing that I converted them both.
I played concentrated and calm and I can't believe I did it," she
said. "But it is beautiful that I take it."
</P>
<P>
It was Davenport's second Grand Slam title against 22 for Graf.
Americans Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi contest the men's final
later on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
