<HEADLINE> Australian PM to Visit Japan, the United States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard said on Sunday that he will discuss economic issues with
leaders of Japan and the United States during his visit to the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Howard is leaving for Tokyo on Monday to begin his two-week
visit to Japan and the United States.
</P>
<P>
In a news briefing for foreign reporters, Howard made it clear
that he would be pressing his Japanese counterpart Keizo Obuchi on
the need for trade reform.
</P>
<P>
He will also press Obuchi on the need for Japan to press ahead
with financial reforms as its economy struggles to overcome the
Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
On Australia's trade with the United States, Howard admitted
that he was still pessimistic about the U.S. moves to impose
tariffs on Australia's lamb exports to the United States.
</P>
<P>
A final decision by the Clinton administration on the issue is
a month overdue now.
</P>
<P>
"I think it indicates they're thinking hard about what we've
put to them, but we're only interested in outcomes," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he would be warning President Bill Clinton and
congressional leaders that any move to unfairly restrict
Australia's lamb trade would set back attempts to further open up
trade in agriculture.
</P>
<P>
During his U.S. trip, Howard will also meet with business and
finance chiefs such as U.S. Federal Reserve chairman Alan
Greenspan, World Bank president James Wolfensohn and chief of the
International Monetary Fund Michael Camdessus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
