<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Veterans Celebrate Soldier's Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Some 300 Yugoslav veterans, who
participated in the 1941-1945 anti-facist war, celebrated the
Soldier's Day on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
These old men and women, mostly in their sixties and seventies
and some even in their eighties, exchanged warm greetings with one
another and discussed about what had happened to their country
since the war against the Nazi Germans.
</P>
<P>
They observed a one-minute silence for those killed in the
recent NATO bombings before starting their annual celebration.
</P>
<P>
Koca Jancic, member of the Yugoslav Anti-Facist War Old
Soldiers Association (SVBNOR), said at the annual gathering that
Yugoslavia is the best example of small nation opposing much
bigger countries in recent history.
</P>
<P>
"Yugoslavia is a nation that dares to fight with stronger enemy
for its own freedom and dignity," said Jancic, "But the NATO
bombings have caused unprecedented humanitarian catastrophy for
this Balkan nation."
</P>
<P>
A Belgrade medical college student, Tanja Nastasic, said that
the younger generation of Serbians not only fought against NATO
attacks with the same bravery and endurance as their parents and
grandparents, but will also demonstrate better capability in the
post-war reconstruction of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav people decided through a special meeting on July 4,
1941, to rise against Nazi occupation of the country. This day
has since been observed as the country's Soldier's day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
