<HEADLINE> Russian, Ukrainian Presidents Hold Informal Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
his Ukrainian counterpart, Leonid Kuchma, on Sunday discussed a
number of issues concerning bilateral ties, including cooperation
in energy and agriculture and on the issue of the Black Sea Fleet.
</P>
<P>
In their informal summit in Yeltsin's Rus country house
outside Moscow, the two leaders agreed that the Black Sea Fleet's
flagship Moskva recently built in Nikolayev would be passed to
Russia, Yeltsin's press secretary Dmitry Yakushkin said.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed a number of international issues,
including the situation in Yugoslavia and the Kosovo settlement.
</P>
<P>
The two also reached agreement that Yeltsin would pay an
official visit to Kiev in September 1999, the Interfax news agency
reported, quoting Kuchma's spokesman Alexander Martynenko.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also discussed Ukraine's energy arrears to
Russia. Ukraine owes Russia about 1 billion U.S. dollars in oil
and gas debts, Russian Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin told the
Federation Council, or upper house of parliament, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin said Ukraine had difficulty paying the debts in cash
but the two sides were pondering other ways of payment.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma, who arrived here Saturday, will fly back to Kiev later
Sunday, Yakushkin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
