<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Troops Recapture Tiger Hills In Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- After three days of fierce
fighting, Indian troops Sunday recaptured the strategic Tiger
Hills, a strategic 4,877-metre high peak overlooking the vital
Sringagar-Leh national highway in the Indian side of the line of
control (LOC) in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The recapture was announced by the Defense Minister George
Fernandes in Amritsar, 447 km northwest of here, according to the
Press Trust of India (PTI).
</P>
<P>
Fernandes said that he had been informed by the Army chief V.
P. Malik about the recapture of the Tiger Hills, a key bastion and
supply camp of the so-called intruders in the Kargil region of
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
On the news of recapture, Indian caretaker Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee announced Sunday that Indian troops had achieved
"tremendous success" in evicting entrenched Pakistani "intruders"
in Kargil.
</P>
<P>
At a function in the state of Haryana, Vajpayee appealed to the
nation to be united to win the conflict with neighboring Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
His defense minister Fernandes said in Amritsar that the
recapture of the hills paved the way to throw out "intruders" to
the other side of the LOC.
</P>
<P>
"We will now be able to dictate terms to the intruders. Our
army is in a position to do anything," Fernandes reportedly told
the Indian troops.
</P>
<P>
With recapture of the key position, Fernandes said, Indian
would consider any concrete proposal from Pakistan at the
diplomatic level to end the stand-off in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister made it clear that military action in
Kargil would not be effected by talks at the diplomatic level.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that India respected the LOC and would not like
to violate it. But he added if needed "nobody can prevent us from
doing so."
</P>
<P>
Observers here considered the recapture of the Tiger Hills by
the Indian troops as a major turning point in the on-going
conflict between Indian and Pakistan in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
For India, the victory would considerably reduce the threat to
its vital Srinagar-Leh strategic national highway, the life-line
for Indian troops in Kashmir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
