<DOCNO> XIE19990704.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Band Organizers Deny Deal with SOCOG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- A company denies that a deal has
been done which cuts the children out of the opening ceremony,
reports said from Sydney on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Initial plans to have 1,500 foreign students perform at the
opening ceremony were shelved following a public backlash in
Australia. The band members raised their own money to perform at
the Games and threatened legal action when SOCOG backed out of the
deal.
</P>
<P>
SOCOG president Michael Knight said Saturday the agreement had
been reached with World Projects Internationaln, but that
organization, which had a contract to supply American and Japanese
school marching band members for the Sydney Olympics, denied any
deal.
</P>
<P>
WPI president Bill Lutt issued a statement Sunday saying the
company had "an enforceable and binding contract to assemble a
Sydney 2000 Olympic Band to perform at the opening ceremony''.
</P>
<P>
"World Projects is continuing to perform under the contract.
Rehearsals are taking place in Australia, North America and Japan,
" the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Knight said Sunday that SOCOG had put what it believed was a
good offer on the table and it was now up to WPI to deliver.
</P>
