<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vajpayee Refuses Clinton's Invitation For U.S. Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Indian caretaker Prime Minister
Atal Behari Vajpayee had expressed his inability "at this stage"
to undertake a visit to the United States, a spokesman of the
External Affairs Ministry disclosed here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton on Saturday invited Vajpayee to
visit Washington "at an early date" for discussions apparently on
the on-going conflict between India and Pakistan in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Clinton extended the invitation during
his 10-minute telephone conversation with Vajpayee last night.
</P>
<P>
The Indian leader told Clinton that it would "not be possible
for him to accept this kind of invitation for the present" and
"not convenient at this stage," the spokesman told a daily news
briefing here.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. leader's invitation was "bilateral" in
nature and had "no relation whatsoever to Pakistan Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif's visit to Washington" which began Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During their conversation, the spokesman said, Clinton informed
Vajpayee about his telephonic conversation with Sharif earlier.
</P>
<P>
A White House spokesman reportedly said in Washington that
"Sharif requested a meeting and I would assume he is bringing some
ideas on how to resolve the current situation."
</P>
<P>
New Delhi has repeatedly said that there is no question of
having talks with Islamabad till Pakistan pulls back its troops
and extremist elements from the Indian side of the LOC, de facto
border between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the U.S. president had given indication of any
Pakistani proposal to end the conflict, the spokesman declined to
give any further details of the Clinton-Vajpayee talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
