<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hebei Reports Slump In Export Volume </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The six month foreign trade
turnover in north China's Hebei province dropped 20.1 percent from
the same period last year which is attributed to the lingering
effects of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics from provincial customs show that the export
volume dropped 32.3 percent to 570 million US dollars during the
January-June period, with the import volume edging up 0.7 percent
to 550 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The declining foreign trade is an indication of the deepening
impact of the Asian financial crisis," said a provincial trade
official. The province's exports to Asian nations declined about
40 percent during the first half year period on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the province's exports to Asian countries have
shrank from the 68.4 percent at the end of 1998 to 53.6 for the
first six month period this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, expanding exports to Europe, North America and Latin
American have offset part of the negative impact, as exports to
countries in the three regions surged 54 percent, 32 percent and
21 percent respectively, with exports to them during the first six
months rising to 36.2 percent of the provincial total from the 28.
7 percent at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The sluggish foreign trade has also forced us to optimize the
product mix of export goods," said the trade official, pointing to
the fact that industrial products, machinery and electronics
products have gradually replaced the primary goods as leaders in
Hebei's export league table. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
