<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Sports Minister Resigns Ahead of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Minister of Sport and
Youth Mohammad Kheir Mamsar has submitted his resignation one
month ahead of the Pan-Arab Games to be held in Amman, the
semi-official Jordan Times reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Abdul Raouf Rawabdeh announced the minister`s
decision to resign after a cabinet meeting on Saturday, but said
the fate of the minister would be decided by King Abdullah Bin
Hussein, who is abroad on a four-nation tour of Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Rawabdeh did not give any reasons for the resignation of
Mamsar.
</P>
<P>
Jordan Times quoted an unnamed senior sports official as
saying the government was dissatisfied with Mamsar`s attempt to
"politicize his ministry with regards to the issue of the Kuwaiti
prisoners."
</P>
<P>
Mamsar pledged to Kuwait during his recent visit to the Gulf
emirate to take efforts to get Kuwaiti prisoners, captured during
the 1990 Gulf crisis, released from Iraqi custody.
</P>
<P>
His visit was aimed at persuading Kuwait to drop its threat to
boycott the Pan-Arab games to be held in Amman in August as
Jordan has announced it welcomed Iraq to take part in the
event.
</P>
<P>
However, Kuwaiti officials said last week that their country
would take part in the games if Iraq "releases a single Kuwaiti
prisoner," but Baghdad denied it kept any Kuwaitis in its
prisons, Jordan Times said.
</P>
<P>
The prisoner issue remained sensitive between Iraq and Kuwait,
and Kuwait has made the release of Kuwaiti prisoners one of the
preconditions to improve its ties with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Mamsar`s decision to touch upon the prisoner issue was blamed
by the Rawabdhe government as "trying to undertake political
missions which are outside his jurisdiction," Jordan Times said.
</P>
<P>
He had planned to travel to Baghdad this month to meet
President Saddam Hussein to mediate for the release of Kuwaiti
prisoners, unconfirmed reports said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been trying to strike a delicate diplomatic balance
between Iraq and Kuwait and officials said Jordan welcomed all
Arab countries, including Iraq, to attend the Arab games in Amman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
