<DOCNO> XIE19990704.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Ministers Sign Undated Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Only three Nigerian ministers sworn
in last week by President Olusegun Obasanjo were exempted from
signing their letters of resignation, said the Guardian, a leading
Nigerian newspaper Sunday.
</P>
<P>
They are Lt-General Theophilus Danjuma (Defense), Chief Bola
Ige (Power and Steel) and Mohammed Arzika (Communications).
</P>
<P>
As part of the measures put in place by Obasanjo to ensure a
corrupt- free government, he had directed that all ministers
except the three sign undated letters of resignation.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the president told The Guardian on Sunday that
Obasanjo adopted the measure to ensure that corrupt ministers are
shown the way out of the government immediately. The three
ministers may have been exempted because of the confidence
Obasanjo has in them.
</P>
<P>
It was learnt president Obasanjo is determined to run a
corrupt-free government to ensure that his government succeeds.
</P>
<P>
This, however, is not the first time a civilian government will
compel its ministers to sign their letters of resignation.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Shehu Shagari, Nigeria's Second Republic President
compelled his ministers to sign their letters of resignation
before they were sworn in 1983 after he had been re-elected.
</P>
<P>
A monitoring team in the presidency to supervise the ministries
and their activities has also been put in place by Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
The monitoring team is charged with the responsibility of
supervising all the activities in the Presidency to determine the
success or the failure of such ministries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990704.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin Gets Thumbs Up From Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 70 percent of overseas
funded businesses in northern Tianjin Municipality are satisfied
with the improvement in the city's investment climate, according
to a recent survey.
</P>
<P>
Compared to a similar survey in 1997 in which the reaction was
not so glowing, most respondents say they are impressed by
improvements in the elimination of arbitrary fees, government
efficiency, labor quality, free market competition, and power and
water supply.
</P>
<P>
Over 12 percent of the respondents said they are "very
satisfied" with 55 percent expressing moderate satisfaction. Only
4.8 percent responded negatively.
</P>
<P>
And well over 75% percent of the respondents said they would
still choose Tianjin as an investment destination if they were
granted a second chance.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted among 540 overseas funded business in
Tianjin, and targeted at their key officials.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin is known to have absorbed the largest amount of
overseas funds of any north China cities. It has approved a total
of 12,000 overseas funded ventures so far, involving contractual
investment of more than 24 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the down side, most respondents are not satisfied with the
traffic conditions, living environment and entertainment
facilities in the city. They have also called for improvements in
legal consulting services and more rational pricing of land and
real estate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
