<DOCNO> XIE19990704.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Blasts Western Pressure on Air Corridors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Russia said Sunday that it was "
stunned" by the refusal of Hungary, Bulgaria and Romania to
provide air corridors to its peacekeepers flying to Kosovo under
pressure from the United States.
</P>
<P>
It said all references to improperly coordinated technical
details of locating Russian paratroopers in Kosovo are absolutely
unfounded, the Interfax news agency reported, quoting sources with
the Russian Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Denial of air corridors by Hungary, Romania and Bulgaria
forced Russia to postpone indefinitely the departure of two
military transport aircraft for Kosovo originally scheduled for
early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Washington and its NATO allies reportedly want to work out
details of Russia's peacekeeping role in Kosovo before Moscow
sends any new troops to augment its about 400 troops already
stationed in the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
Western media reports said that Russian military negotiators
last week sought to alter an agreement reached earlier in Helsinki
by having their troops in Kosovo report only to Russian officers,
rather than be under the formal command of NATO. Russia also
wants to station forces in the Italian, French, American and
German sectors of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
However, a representative with the Russian Defense Ministry
said, "All details of the location of Russian peacekeepers in
Kosovo were documented during the talks held by the defense and
foreign ministers in Helsinki."
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, these details were updated during the talks held
in Brussels this week by Deputy Head of the Defense Ministry's
Department for International Military Cooperation Valentin
Kuznetsov.
</P>
<P>
Mistrust has been mounting between Moscow and the U.S.-led
NATO following Russia's surprise deployment of 200 troops to
Pristina airport last month and an usual military exercise about
two weeks ago in which American F-15 jets intercepted Russian
fighter-bombers near Iceland.
</P>
<P>
The two Il-76 planes were to have taken off from the Severny
airport near the city of Ivanovo early Sunday. One plane was to
carry two heavy-duty trucks, technological equipment and a
maintenance team. The other was to take over 100 paratroopers and
a group of reporters to cover the peacekeeping mission in the
Balkans, the Itar-Tass news agency reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990704.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taylor: Foreign Players Destroy Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 4 (Xinhua)-- the influx of foreign players into
English clubs was destroying the game, said professional
Footballers' Association chief executive Gordon Taylor on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Though England may win the bid to stage the 2006 World Cup
there might not be a host team good enough to distinguish itself,
the boss was quoted by a report as saying.
</P>
<P>
Taylor also said he was increasingly dismayed with the influx
of foreign players into English football, forcing more out of work
and affecting the chances of all the youngsters trying to break
through.
</P>
<P>
Players' union boss Taylor reckons that the Government's
decision this week to relax work permit rules for players outside
the European Union could even have a detrimental effect on the
international set-up.
</P>
<P>
"We can't deny work permits to those from the European Union,"
admitted Taylor. "But I've been very disappointed this week that
the Government has sought to relax work permit regulations for
players outside of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
"We could now get players who are not better but merely cheaper,
maybe from eastern Europe and Africa where economies are lower."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
