<HEADLINE> Ferguson Blames Government for FA Cup Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Sir Alex Ferguson says government
pressure left Manchester United with no choice but to pull out of
the FA Cup.
</P>
<P>
Instead of defending the trophy the treble-winners will travel
to Brazil for the World Team Championship next January.
</P>
<P>
The Football Association offered United the option of missing
next season's competition.
</P>
<P>
It was feared that snibbing the new FIFA tournament would
damage England's hopes of staging the 2006 World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
United upset their fans by taking up that offer, but Labour
supporter Sir Alex says Sports Minister Tony Banks left his club
with no choice.
</P>
<P>
"In the last week we have been under considerable pressure from
the government," said the United boss.
</P>
<P>
"It is easy for everyone to criticise Manchester United but if
you read the statement from Sports Minister Tony Banks it said '
Manchester United must go'.
</P>
<P>
"It expressed what they feel. I was so determined for us to
stay in the FA Cup and defend our Treble, but it was clear the
government wanted us to go to Brazil," Ferguson told the News of
the World.
</P>
<P>
"They are on a crusade for the World Cup. If it wasn't for the
World Cup Man Utd would not be involved in Brazil - it's as simple
as that."
</P>
<P>
In separate Sunday newspaper reports, Banks blames threats from
FIFA officials for the situation.
</P>
<P>
"I happen to know, as a member of the World Cup campaign
committee, that if Manchester United hadn't gone to Brazil it
would have destroyed our chances of staging the 2006 World Cup
finals," he told the Mail on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the Sunday Mirror quotes him as saying: "Three
members of FIFA, who had been very much in favor of our bid said
to my face that if United don't take part they'd change their
minds.
</P>
<P>
"Their argument was that we can't pick and choose, wanting to
host the World Cup but not taking part in one of FIFA's
competitions.
</P>
<P>
"I have the names of those who said it would do damage."
</P>
