<HEADLINE> Sports Minister: Cup Snub was United Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- British Sports minister Tony Banks
has hit back at claims from Sir Alex Ferguson that Manchester
United were pressured by the Government into competing in the
World Club Championships next season.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson has admitted that over the last few days United "have
been under considerable pressure from the Government" who he
believes "are on a crusade for the World Cup."
</P>
<P>
The Old Trafford boss reckons that but for the World Cup - with
a decision to be made on the venue for the 2006 event in March
just two months after the Championships in Brazil - his side would
have gladly defended the FA Cup, and ultimately the Treble.
</P>
<P>
United's participation, following their Champions Cup victory
over Bayern Munich in May, was seen as crucial for England to host
the premier tournament 40 years after they last staged it.
</P>
<P>
If United had declined, then Bayern would have taken up the
offer, handing the initiative to Germany, who along with South
Africa are England's main rivals in the bidding.
</P>
<P>
Banks, however, is adamant that it was United's decision all
along, saying "Exceptional circumstances have caused this
situation to arise.
</P>
<P>
"But this is something Manchester United were happy to do and
the idea that I personally have forced them to do it is a rather
interesting story.
</P>
<P>
"I hope Mr Blair (the Prime Minister) realises just how
powerful I am in domestic and world football."
</P>
<P>
But Ferguson is convinced the ultimate decision was out of
United's hands. He added: "It is easy for everyone to criticise
Manchester United.
</P>
<P>
"But if you read the statement from Sports Minister Tony Banks
it said 'Manchester United must go'. It expressed what they feel.
I was so determined for us to stay in the FA Cup and defend our
Treble but it was clear the Government wanted us to go to Brazil."
</P>
</TEXT>
