<HEADLINE> Former Israeli FM Returns to Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Former Israeli foreign minister
David Levy will return to his post almost one and a half years
after resigning from the government of outgoing Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, Israel Radio reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak, Levy told
the radio that Barak has officially informed him that he will
become the next foreign minister in the new government, which is
expected to be sworn in Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Levy's appointment has been widely expected since his Gesher
party joined in Barak's One Israel alliance, which combines the
Labor Party, Gesher and the moderate religious party Meimad,
before the May election.
</P>
<P>
Under the alliance agreement, Levy was given the number three
post in the parliamentary list of One Israel, after Barak and
former prime minister Shimon Peres.
</P>
<P>
Barak won a landslide victory in the prime minister race and
his One Israel seized 26 seats in the 120-member parliament.
</P>
<P>
After resigning from the right-wing Likud, Levy formed Gesher,
a party of Middle East Jews, before the 1996 elections. Netanyahu
persuaded him to lead his party into alliance with the Likud in
the election and appointed him foreign minister in the Likud
government.
</P>
<P>
But Levy resigned in January 1998, unhappy with the hard-line
policy of Netanyahu on the peace process and the alleged
mistreatment of the low-income class.
</P>
<P>
With his five-seat Gesher breaking off with the coalition,
Netanyahu's government was pushed to the edge of collapse with
only a slim majority of 61 seats in the 120-member parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
