<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Cabinet Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Kuwaiti cabinet Sunday
submitted resignation to Emir Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah, shortly
after the results of the country's parliamentary elections were
officially announced.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet tabled the mass resignation under the country's
constitution, which stipulates that the government shall resign
once the results of the National Assembly (Parliament) emerged.
</P>
<P>
The emir accepted the cabinet's resignation and entrusted it
to act as a care-taking government until a new cabinet is formed
within two weeks, the official news agency KUNA reported.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to the emir, Crown Prince and Prime Minister
Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Salem Al-Sabah said that he was charged
with the premiership task at one of the most critical stages of
the country's history, which required cooperation of all
authoritative departments.
</P>
<P>
"The government had succeeded in making many achievements for
the sake of serving interests of the country and its citizens as
a result of the sincere efforts of the natives," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The present cabinet was formed in March 1998 after a mass
resignation of the previous government due to a dispute with the
then parliament, which pushed the relations between the executive
and legislative branches into a dead end.
</P>
<P>
Ties between the two authorities often remain a major source of
parliament dissolution and cabinet resignation. Cooperation
crisis triggered by policy differences led to the dissolution of
the last parliament on May 4.
</P>
<P>
According to official results announced earlier Sunday morning,
14 liberals and 20 Islamic candidates, both represent the
opposition groups, were elected to the new parliament in what is
probably the country's last all-male elections.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the opposition ranks enjoy a comfortable
two-thirds majority in the 50-member parliament signals possible
confrontations between the next cabinet and the newly-elected
parliament, analysts here said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
