<HEADLINE> Cooperatives Active in Economic Development in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Cooperatives in Myanmar have been
playing an active role in the country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures released by the Myanmar Ministry of
Cooperatives on Sunday, a total of 9,410 agricultural producers
cooperatives and agricultural and general merchandise cooperatives
have been formed in the agricultural sector to cultivate crops.
</P>
<P>
In the industrial sector, 1,506 industrial producers
cooperatives (IPC) have been formed, producing small and medium
machines and parts, fertilizer, farm equipment and engines as well
as carrying out repair and lathe works to assist agricultural
production.
</P>
<P>
In the financial sector, a total of 2,042 credit cooperatives
have also been formed in various parts of the country to meet the
financial need of the people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, trading cooperatives and exporting cooperatives have
also been established. The exporting cooperatives have reportedly
earned 19.9 million U.S. dollars in the fiscal year 1998-99 which
ended in March.
</P>
<P>
In Myanmar, cooperatives movement started in 1904 and the
credit cooperative society formed then was the very first
cooperative society in the country.
</P>
<P>
The cooperatives contributed 2.1 percent to the gross domestic
product annually in the past few years, making up 2.3 percent in
volume in the trade sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
