<HEADLINE> Zambia and Angola Mend Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Zambian government said that the
relations between Zambia and Angola is getting better, Sunday Mail
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Minister Keli Walubita was quoted by the paper
as saying Saturday in an interview in Ndola, Copperbelt Province,
that the fact Angola sent its deputy minister of defence and
security for the Congo (K) peace talks in Lusaka was an indication
that Angola was ready to restore good relations with Zambia. "This
is a step in the right direction and I am optimistic that the two
countries will once again renew the mutual relationship," Walubita
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he will be leaving for Algeria on Sunday for an
Organization of African Unity Summit to seek a lasting solution
for the differences between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Walubita said that the meeting held recently between Angola and
Zambia was fruitful. "Another meeting at which further
deliberations will be made is being organized and soon the two
countries shall be good friends again like it was in the past," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Angola had been persistently accusing Zambia of providing
logistical and military support to the Jonas Savimbi-led the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) rebel
movement fighting the government of President Edwardo dos Santos.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government, however, denied all the charges and
challenged Angola to prove the allegations.
</P>
<P>
At the Swaziland meeting held last month, the two countries
agreed to improve relations between them. In the meeting Zambia
had accepted the proposal by Angola to forget the past and start
on a new chapter.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed that a ministerial meeting be
held as soon as possible to arrange for a meeting of the heads of
state of two countries.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
