<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Theft Endangers Parliament Treasures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The recent theft of a
treasured diamond ring from South African Parliament has enraged
the art community and raised fears about the security of the
balance of a 20 million rand (3.3 million U. S. dollars) family
collection left in the state's hands 80 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The ring, worth at least 200,000 rand (33,000 dollars) and
stolen last week, pushes the value of goods stolen from the
Parliament in five years to more than one million rand (166,000
dollars) and raises security concerns at the complex. It also
casts doubt on whether Parliament should be a custodian of
national treasures, the Sunday Times reported.
</P>
<P>
Besides theft, recent flooding of Parliament's basement library
have also damaged valuable books and paintings.
</P>
<P>
The collection, which includes 7,000 books and 300 paintings,
was bequeathed to the South African government by diamond magnate
Sidney Mendlssohn in 1917. It is the second most important
collection of African books in the country -- after that of the
South African Library -- and is estimated to be worth more than 20
million rand (3.3 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Parliament has been taking stock of what remains of the
collection-- and what may have been stolen from the library after
a spate of thefts over the years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
