<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Planes' Departure for Kosovo Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Denial of air corridors by Hungary,
Romania and Bulgaria forced Russia to postpone the departure of
two military transport aircraft for Kosovo originally scheduled
for early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The flights have been postponed indefinitely, the Itar-Tass
news agency reported, noting that the three country's refusal to
let Russia use their airspace appeared to be a result of pressure
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Washington and its NATO allies want to work out details of
Russia's peacekeeping role in the Kosovo before Moscow sends any
new troops to augment its presence of about 400 troops already in
the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
Western media reports said that Russian military negotiators
last week sought to alter an agreement reached earlier in Helsinki
by having their troops in Kosovo report only to Russian officers,
rather than being placed under the formal command of NATO.
</P>
<P>
Russia also reportedly wanted to station forces in the Italian,
French, American and German sectors of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Mistrust has been mounting between Moscow and the U.S.-led NATO
following Russia's surprise deployment of 200 troops to Pristina
airport last month and an usual military exercise about two weeks
ago in which American F-15 jets intercepted Russian fighter-
bombers near Iceland.
</P>
<P>
The two Il-76 planes were to have taken off from the Severny
airport near the city of Ivanovo early Sunday. One plane was to
carry two heavy-duty trucks, technological equipment and a
maintenance team. The other was to take about 100 paratroopers and
a group of reporters to cover the peacekeeping mission in the
Balkans, Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
In another related development, Russia last week ordered an
American military attache to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant-Colonel Peter Hoffman, the assistant Army attache at
the U.S. Embassy in Moscow, was declared persona non grata and
left Russia Thursday evening, The New York Times reported Sunday,
quoting U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
The expulsion represented another sign of the growing tension
between Moscow and Washington in the aftermath of NATO's 78-day
air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
It was unclear what caused Hoffman's expulsion. Russia's
Federal Security Service, the main successor to the KGB, refused
to comment, directing the question to the Foreign Ministry, which
remained silent on the incident.
</P>
<P>
According to U.S. officials, Hoffman, a specialist in military
intelligence, participated in the negotiations in Helsinki on
peacekeeping operations in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
One U.S. administration official speculated that the expulsion
might have been a response to a recent decision by the United
States to expel an official at Russia's mission to the United
States on accusations of spying, The New York Times reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
