<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 08:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberals Make Comeback in Kuwaiti Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Liberals in Kuwait made a
surprising comeback by securing 14 seats in Saturday's parliament
elections, thus adding force to the opposition ranks while dealing
a heavy blow to the government.
</P>
<P>
Official results announced early Sunday morning showed that

liberals, which held only three seats in the last parliament
dissolved in May, secured 14 seats in the 50-member National
Assembly (Parliament) this time.
</P>
<P>
Although pro-Islamic candidates lost four seats by winning only
20 seats, the combined liberal and Islamic opposition now
controls a comfortable two-third majority in the parliament,
indicating potential confrontations between the parliament and
government.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen seats went to other candidates, among whom most are
pro-government tribal figures.
</P>
<P>
The final results also showed that Kuwaiti voters again
extended their support to intellectuals and younger people by
choosing 47 well-educated and young candidates for the new
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Of the 50 new parliament members, over 85 percent received
college or higher education, while more than 55 percent are under
the age of 50.
</P>
<P>
In Saturday's elections, scorching summer heat failed to quit
Kuwaiti voters. Nearly 80 percent of the 113,000 eligible male
voters turned out to cast ballots at 190 polling stations in 25
constituencies nationwide.
</P>
<P>
A total of 288 registered candidates contested in what is
likely to be the country's last all-male elections.
</P>
<P>
Since there are no official political parties in Kuwait,
candidates are representing different government-tolerated
political groups. Some prominent and influential political figures
are even running as independents.
</P>
<P>
The previous parliament was constitutionally dissolved by Emir
Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah on May 4, on the grounds that the
legislature misused the constitutional rights and violated ethics
and morals of the conservative Gulf Arab state.
</P>
<P>
During the two-month elections campaign, domestic issues,
especially the economic ones, dominated the campaign platforms of
most candidates.
</P>
<P>
The candidates called on the private sector to play a more
important role in the country's economy by employing more
national manpower, and promised to work on it if elected.
</P>
<P>
Some candidates also focused their speeches on the importance
of cooperation between the parliament and government.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation crisis triggered by policy differences led to the
unreconcilable relations between the legislative and executive
authorities, as well as the mass resignation of the former
cabinet in March 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
