<HEADLINE> Pro-Israeli Militia Leader Decides to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Commander of the pro-Israeli South
Lebanon Army (SLA) Antoine Lahd has decided to quit his post one
month after his militia completed a withdrawal from the southern
Lebanese town of Jezzine.
</P>
<P>
The Voice of the People radio Sunday quoted sources coming
from the Israeli occupied border zone in south Lebanon as saying
that the 70-year-old commander had conveyed his resolve to quit
the post to Israeli authorities.
</P>
<P>
He told the Israeli authorities that his decision was
irrevocable and he wanted to go to Paris to meet his family, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Lahd's family has been living in France since he survived an
assassination attempt at his house in Marjayoun inside the
occupied zone 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Along with other SLA senior officials, Lahd has been sentenced
to death in absentia by a Lebanese military court for
collaborating with Israel which is considered as Lebanon's enemy.
</P>
<P>
The 2,500-strong militia was trained and funded by Israel to
help it patrol the border zone where the Jewish state occupied in
1985 as a buffer zone to protect its north.
</P>
<P>
The militia has been policing Jezzine, the largest Christian
town in south Lebanon, just north of the zone, until it abandoned
it early last month under the pressure of Hezbollah's intensified
bombing attacks around the area.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, is leading a war
of attrition to oust Israeli troops and SLA out of the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, Israel is seeking an alternative
from several candidates to replace Lahd, the radio said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
