<DOCNO> XIE19990704.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Danger to Zimbabwe's National Unity: Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's ruling Zanu (PF)
officials and some political scientists have ruled out as "total
wishful thinking" predictions that the death of Vice-President
Joshua Nkomo may lead to the end of national unity, the Sunday
Mail reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Nkomo died in Harare on Thursday and will be buried at the
National Heroes Acre on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some pessimists and critics of the Unity Accord between former
Zimbabwe African People's Union (ZAPU) and Zimbabwe African
National Union (ZANU) signed by Nkomo and President Robert Mugabe
on December 22, 1987, had said his death was not just a tragedy
but was a "major test of the unity".
</P>
<P>
Minister of Local Government and National Housing John Nkomo
said there were those people who hope that the unity will
collapse.
</P>
<P>
He said late Nkomo had left a legacy, a legacy of peace and
stability, which had to be nurtured. "We hope that everyone will
do his or her best to see that our unity succeeds," he said.
</P>
<P>
Former secretary of the late veteran nationalist in the days of
the struggle and now Minister of Mines, Environment and Tourism
Simon Moyo said the challenge confronting Zimbabweans was that of
sustaining the unity Nkomo helped forge about 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Moyo said late Nkomo was a national Vice-President and not of
Matabeleland province only.
</P>
<P>
"That assertion that unity will collapse can only come from
people who never worked with him, people with a short vision.
Nobody owned him in terms of region, he was not shortsighted,"
Moyo said.
</P>
<P>
A well-known political scientist of Zimbabwe, Professor
Jonathan Moyo said late Nkomo was a man of vision who had realized
the importance of national unity by spearheading the merger of
Zapu and Zanu (PF) in 1987.
</P>
<P>
He said people should only hope that he has not departed with
the peace and that the entire nation was enjoying.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of succession, Moyo said it was very important for
people to realize that no province had a natural right to the
Vice-Presidency, adding that this was better left for the National
Congress to decide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
