<HEADLINE> Automobile Sales in UAE Falling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- After scoring a record high in
1998, automobile sales in the United Arab Emirates (UAE) are
showing signs of slowing down during the first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The shipments of passenger cars and sports utility vehicles
into the UAE during the period are estimated to close at the
28,000-29,000 mark against 35,000 in the first six months of 1998,
down by nearly 15 percent, the Gulf News daily reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Total shipments to the local automobile market reached 90,000
units last year, a record high in recent years, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Car industry sources are divided as to the factors causing the
slowdown.
</P>
<P>
"While it may have been difficult to match the record run of
1998, factors for the slowdown appear more deep-rooted. Buyers are
not rushing to the showrooms despite being offered some of the
most competitive rates in years," a senior official with a
U.S. car maker was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Our feedback shows that they are more inclined to wait a
while longer and wait for the 2000 models to hit the markets
later this year," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, other sources suggested that high region-wide
inventories for all manufacturers had led to increased price
competition and a distorted sales picture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
