<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Manila Tries Hard to Spur Bank Lending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- If the "Guinness Book of World
Records" listed the frequency of interest rate cuts, then the
Central Bank of the Philippines could be recorded.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Central Bank of the Philippines will cut for the
20th time this year its key overnight rates by 12.5 basis points
to encourage a resumption in bank lending.
</P>
<P>
After the new round of rate cut, the bank's overnight borrowing
rate will be reduced to 9 percent from 9.125 percent, while its
lending rate to 11 percent from 11.125 percent.
</P>
<P>
This will bring the bank's cumulative reduction since the start
of the year to 437.5 basis points.
</P>
<P>
"This move along with the 2 percentage point reduction in the
reserve requirement effective yesterday (last Thursday), reflects
the sustained efforts of the Monetary Board (of the central bank)
to bring down the cost of bank lending while ensuring adequate
liquidity in the system," said Central Bank Governor Gabriel
Singson last Friday when he announced the rate cut.
</P>
<P>
To induce banks to relax tight credit conditions, the central
bank last Thursday already cut the reserve requirement of
commercial banks by 2 percentage points to 12 percent, a move that
would release billions of potentially lendable funds into the
banking system.
</P>
<P>
The latest move by the central bank took many people by
surprise, as the U.S. Federal Reserve Board slightly increased its
short-term rates only days ago. The hike, as some people said,
could force other countries to raise their interest rates.
</P>
<P>
But the central bank said the cut in the overnight rates was
undertaken in the belief that the inflation rate for June would be
lower than 6.7 percent registered in May and the U.S. rate hike
would have no bearing at all on the Philippines' domestic market.
</P>
<P>
"The (local) market has already discounted the hike in the Fed
rate," Singson said.
</P>
<P>
Why does the central bank of the Philippines so desperately cut
its overnight rates nearly every week in the past six months?
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the central bank has to do so as the country's
commercial banks still have reservations about extending loans to
companies because they have to clear their book of non-performing
loans.
</P>
<P>
With the volume of total loans contracting and unpaid
obligations mounting, non-performing loans of commercial banks in
the Philippines climbed to 14.48 percent of total loans in April,
compared with 13.18 percent in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, despite significant cuts in the central bank's key
rates and its mandatory reserve requirements, commercial banks
have remained tight-fisted.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest figures released by the central bank,
bank lending declined further to 1.68 trillion pesos (about 442
million U.S. dollars) in April, a 2.7-percent contraction from the
year-ago level.
</P>
<P>
As the non-performing ratio has yet to peak this year,
commercial banks in the country are unlikely to change course in
regard to new lending even if the central bank continues to ease
its monetary policy, economists here said.
</P>
<P>
But Singson said the steady drop in interest rates is expected
to boost corporate demand for credit and will also help ease
corporate stress by easing leverage ratios and improving repayment
capacity of firms.
</P>
<P>
Facing a tough task of spurring bank lending, incoming Central
Bank Governor Rafael Buenaventura, who will assume office Monday,
said there will be "no radical changes" in the current monetary
policy, with the focus still on further easing interest rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
