<HEADLINE> Brazil through to Last Eight at Copa America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Reigning champions Brazil
advanced into the last eight of the Copa America, or South
American football championships, after winning 2-1 over Mexico in
Ciudad del Este, Paraguay, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The win added to Brazil's opening 7-0 victory over Venezuela
earlier at the championships.
</P>
<P>
Italy-based duo Ronaldo and Amoroso were obviously the heroes
of the game, with Parma's Amoroso racing onto a pass from the
Inter Milan man to put the Brazilians one up after 19 minutes,
beating Mexico's flamboyant goalkeeper Jorge Campos.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's strikeforce of Luis Hernandez and Cuahtemoc Blanco did
not get the service they needed to really trouble the Mexican
defence.
</P>
<P>
New talent Alex, who plays for Palmeiras, made it 2-0 for the
defending champions when his ferocious shot from 25 yards away
found the net before the halftime.
</P>
<P>
Mexico, who are competing as specially invited guests alongside
Japan, came back strongly in the second period. They narrowed the
gap after 73 minutes through substitute Isaac Terrazas who
replaced Paulo Cesar Chavez at the interval.
</P>
<P>
Brazil had one of the sides' best players sent off seven
minutes from time as Barcelona midfielder Rivaldo was showned a
red card. But that did not stop the South Americans held on for a
deserved 2-1 win over their Central American counterparts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
