<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Help Maldives in Drug Detection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will send narcotics crime
busters for the first time to the Maldives to help it in its fight
against the drug menace, police sources said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Two handlers from the Sri Lankan Police Department's kennels
division accompanied by their canine partners will leave for the
Maldives this month, following a formal request for assistance by
the Maldivian government.
</P>
<P>
The Maldives has seen an increase in illegal drugs smuggling
through its air and sea ports. So it has turned to Sri Lanka for
urgent assistance despite being a Muslim nation with a general
aversion toward dogs.
</P>
<P>
The operation to deploy Sri Lankan police personnel will be
fine-tuned regularly and the handlers rotated every three months,
said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the Maldivians have been impressed by the
professionalism and detection record of the Sri Lankan Police
Department's kennels division.
</P>
<P>
The Maldives is not the only country to have recognized the
caliber of manpower and training at the kennels division, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
At a recent regional conference of South Asia, Nepal too had
requested training for its police officers in canine crime
busting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
