<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Eyes Neighboring Electric Wire Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is eyeing the huge
electric wire markets in neighboring countries and hopes to export
its surplus production to India, Nepal and Myanmar, The Daily Star
Business reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Local electric wire manufacturer, Paradise Cables Limited
(PCL), plans to step up its exports to the three countries, a
senior company official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We are particularly looking at markets in India and Nepal
where there is a huge demand for Bangladeshi electric cables,"
said PCL Chairman Mosharraf Hossain.
</P>
<P>
Hossain said the PCL had already received small orders from
these countries and were expecting more from Myanmar. "But we want
to enter the markets in a bigger way."
</P>
<P>
"We need special tariff facilities to compete with the wire
producers of India and other countries," as "only special tariff
facilities could boost our exports to the regional markets since
there is a huge demand for Bangladeshi wires in other South Asian
countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh produces 20,000 tons of electric cables annually, of
which the PCL production accounts for 20 percent, and domestic
demand is only 12,000 tons a year, according to Hossain.
</P>
<P>
"We need to export our surplus products which would help reduce
the country's trade gap with neighbors, particularly India," he
said.
</P>
<P>
PCL, which is trying to expand its product range, mainly
imports copper from Chile and aluminum from Australia and India.
"Now we are producing fire-proof cross-linked polyethylene and are
likely to start production optical fiber cables by 2001," he said.
</P>
<P>
Limited demand for optical fiber cables in the country means
that PCL would make such cables for export only. "For home market
production, we need government guarantees for local consumption,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
