<HEADLINE> Cabinet Reshuffle Only Covers Vacant Posts: Thai PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Only vacant posts will be refilled
in the upcoming government reshuffle, Channel 9, the state TV
station, Sunday morning quoted Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Speaking Saturday night upon his arrival in Bangkok from
provinces, Chuan said fresh blood is expected to be absorbed into
the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Chuan had said earlier that the post of Deputy Prime Minister
and Commerce Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi, who is running for
the director-generalship of the World Trade Organization (WTO),
will remain intact since the WTO race is unlikely to produce any
result before the reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
At present, seven cabinet seats are vacant, including those of
deputy agriculture minister, education minister, science minister,
deputy science minister, deputy transportation and communication
minister, deputy industry minister and a deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Agriculture Minister Somchai Sunthornvut of the Democrat
Party resigned earlier due to poor health while Education Minister
Panja Kesornthong from the Chart Thai Party quitted Friday.
</P>
<P>
Both the Democrat Party, the core party of the coalition, and
Chart Pattana Party, the second largest party in the coalition,
are expected to hold executive committee meetings Sunday to
discuss the reshuffle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
