<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Buy Russian Warships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- A top-level Sri Lankan delegation
is visiting the Russian Federation to explore the possibility of
purchasing three warships to counter Tamil rebels' arms smuggling,
press reports here said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The government sent the delegation to inspect several warships
after Russia responded positively to a Sri Lankan bid for fighting
ships that once belonged to the powerful Warsaw Pact fleet,"
reported the Sunday Island.
</P>
<P>
Russian vessels had been in service with the Sri Lankan Navy
(SLN) years ago. However, since the civil war erupted in 1983, Sri
Lanka has not acquired fighting ships from Russia.
</P>
<P>
The vessels on offer are bigger and more powerful than the
SLN's biggest vessel Shakthi, a Chinese-built landing ship tank.
</P>
<P>
The acquisition of big vessels will considerably improve the
SLN's capability to counter Tamil rebels' arms smuggling
operations in international waters, said defense sources.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has been forced to request for Indian naval and air
assistance to counter Tamil rebels' arms smuggling operations due
to lack of big vessels.
</P>
<P>
There are 23 big vessels in the SLN's fleet of 148 craft
deployed against Tamil rebels who have been fighting for a
homeland for minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east since
1983.
</P>
<P>
Navy Commander Vice Admiral Cecil Tissera recently said the
government has identified the need to wage a proper campaign
against Tamil rebels' sea capability.
</P>
<P>
The prestigious Jane's Fighting Ships in its latest issue has
quoted Sri Lankan President Chandrika Kumaratunga as saying, "If
we had upgraded our navy earlier, the problem of Tamil separatist
terrorism would not have taken the present form."
</P>
<P>
It described Kumaratunga's remarks as an unusual tribute to the
importance of sea power, even in local confrontations, for an
island nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
