<HEADLINE> Ecuadorian Government: No Demonstration for Fuel Prices Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Ecuadorian government warned
Saturday that it will not permit the country to be paralyzed by
the threatened demonstration on Monday by taxi drivers in protest
against the hike in fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Vladimiro Alvarez said that President Jamil
Mahuad may issue "a special decree" to prevent social disorders.
</P>
<P>
Gasoline price in Ecuador has risen by 13.1 percent since July
1, and prices for other oil byproducts used in the automotive
sector have also gone up.
</P>
<P>
Taxi drivers plan to repeat the blockade they performed in
March when they parked their cars in the main streets to block
access to major cities in the country.
</P>
<P>
They expect the government to overrule the price increases
before Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
