<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
today's major Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The 9th plenary session of Preparatory Committee for the
Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR) ended in Beijing
Saturday with a number of rulings on Macao's return to the
motherland adopted.
</P>
<P>
-- Provinces along the Yellow River are stepping up preparatory
work in flood-control by keeping close surveillance on
hydrological conditions of the river, mapping out flood-control
plans and coordinating flood-diversion efforts, and increasing
checks on vulnerable sections along the river.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- A new savings option offering higher interest rates, "
educational savings" by name, will soon be unveiled to encourage
the Chinese people to lay up money for the education of their
children, as a part of the government's effort to stimulate the
development of an education industry.
</P>
<P>
-- China is to engage the power of non-state capital to widen
options for spending on schooling and help raise the quality of
the country's labor force. In the new financing system of
education, non-state capital will play the major role in non-
compulsory schooling.
</P>
<P>
"Beijing Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The Chinese capital Beijing started a massive campaign to
improve the city environment Saturday by focusing on tightening
management on environment and stepping up sanitary work. The city
has focused on dismantling illegal buildings to improve the city
look.
</P>
<P>
-- Construction of the state-level grain reserves in Beijing
has gone into the final stage with the completion of the grain
reserve in Shunyi in the northeastern suburbs of Beijing. Five
such state-level grain reserves are planned in Beijing, with a
total grain storage capacity of 375 million kilograms. The state-
level grain reserve system is expected to alleviate the pressure
on that of the city, which needs to store a total of five billion
kilograms of grain annually.  
</P>
