<HEADLINE> Study Says Vitro Fertilization Tried by 20 Percent of Sterile Couples </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Sterility affects 12 percent of
all couples in the world and 20 percent of these couples try vitro
fertilization, according to a study by a Mexican researcher
published here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Arnoldo Guzman, member of the University of Guadalajara
Sciences of Health Center, said that artificial method does not
have the same acceptance level in different countries.
</P>
<P>
All fertilization programs, such as sperm banks and the
practice in which women accept the implanting of an ovule
fertilized in an artificial medium, are legal in Mexico, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, artificial reproduction method has its social
limitations, "because it is an intimate matter, costly, and with
religious and ethical implications," said Guzman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
