<HEADLINE> EU Industry Ministers Highlight Information Tech Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, July 3 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) industry
ministers Saturday agreed that EU countries must improve education
in information and communications technology in order to have
enough work force in this field.
</P>
<P>
Concluding a two-day informal meeting in Oulu, western Finland,
the ministers said a large and qualified labor force is essential
to ensure EU enterprises' competitive edge on the international
market in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also called for more investment in information
technology, to catch up with the United States and Japan, and to
strengthen software service.
</P>
<P>
With "Competitiveness In The Information Society" as main theme,
a summary report was worked out at the meeting to be submitted to
their formal meeting scheduled later this season.
</P>
<P>
The Oulu session, the first at the ministerial level hosted by
Finland after it took over the rotating EU presidency from Germany
on July 1, was shadowed by the boycott of Germany and Austria in
protest of Helsinki's refusal to add German to its working
languages.
</P>
<P>
Under normal EU practice, English, French and the language of
the EU presidency holder are used at informal meetings. 
</P>
