<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Casual Wear Industry Burgeoning in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Casual wear is enjoying widespread
favor from Chinese consumers nowadays and has become one of the
most important elements of China's garment industry, reported the
China Daily's Sunday edition Business Weekly.
</P>
<P>
The advantages of such clothing become more notable since the
current heatwave makes life very uncomfortable for workers trapped
by inflexible company dress codes into wearing suits and ties and
other inappropriate clothing.
</P>
<P>
"As weekends draw near, I almost cannot wait to throw off my
uniform and put on my casual wear," said Sun Yi, an employee of a
US-based company in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
China's casual wear is important for injecting new vitality
into the garment industry, given the currently lackluster domestic
demand and global economic slowdown, said Jiang Hengjie, board
chairman of the China Garment Association.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the China Commercial Information Center
indicate that China exported more than nine billion garments last
year, up four percent from 1997. Of these, almost 25 percent were
casual wear.
</P>
<P>
A second reason for the increasing popularity of casual wear in
China is that people have more spare time than ever before as a
result of the implementation of the two-day weekend in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"Casual wear has become a new economic growth area for the
garment industry, since it is now inseparable from people's daily
life, especially for urban citizens," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
"Although it is still in its primitive stage, the industry is
maintaining a high growth momentum," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, problems such as mediocre design, low quality
accessories and backward knitting skills have hindered the
development of the industry.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the design of the casual wear in China merely copies
from the Western style," said Wang Qin, Secretary-general of the
China Fashion Designers Association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990704.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Stops Russians From Reinforcing Kosovo Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) has refused to allow Russia to fly more troops
into Kosovo until details of their mission have been agreed to,
U.S. officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The alliance expects the Russians this week to continue talks
on the requested revisions, according to an Associated Press
report.
</P>
<P>
Russia wants to send some of its troops into sectors of Kosovo
controlled by other NATO countries beyond the U.S., Germany and
France.
</P>
<P>
However, Washington and its allies believe that Moscow's demand
would change an agreement reached in lengthy negotiations last
month at Helsinki, Finland, that outlined Russian participation in
a NATO-led peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
The AP quoted a U.S. official as saying that NATO will continue
to work with Russian military on the arrangements for Russia's
participation.
</P>
<P>
"It is NATO's view that we should complete all of these
arrangements before additional Russian forces deploy to Kosovo,"
the unidentified official said.
</P>
<P>
The talks between NATO and Russia will last seven to 10 days at
the Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe to work out
deployment details.
</P>
<P>
Russia reportedly asked Hungary, Romania and Bulgaria late last
week for corridors through which Ilyushin cargo planes could fly
soldiers to join about 700 Russian troops and technicians already
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
NATO member Hungary and Romania and Bulgaria, both of which
want to join the alliance, rejected the requests, the AP said.
</P>
<P>
Russia strongly opposed NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia, which has
strained the relations between Moscow and the West.
</P>
<P>
Despite efforts by U.S. President Bill Clinton and Russian
President Boris Yeltsin to mend the fences last month at the G-8
summit in Germany, disputes still remain on Russia's participation
of peacekeeping in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
