<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras to Meet Agassi in Wimbledon Men's Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Pete Sampras and
fellow American Andre Agassi will vie for the men's singles title
of the Wimbledon tennis championships on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Top seed Sampras defeated local hero Tim Henman 3-6, 6-4, 6-3,
6-4 on Saturday and is on course for his sixth title in seven
years -- a record this century.
</P>
<P>
Fourth seed Agassi outclassed Australian second seed Pat Rafter
7-5, 7-6, 6-2 and is now just one win away from being the first
player for 19 years to win the French Open and Wimbledon titles in
the same season.
</P>
<P>
Agassi's win returned him to the top of the rankings,
surpassing Sampras, for the first time since February 1996 and
caps an extraordinary comeback by the American who was ranked
122nd at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
"It's a highly anticipated match, by everybody including myself.
I haven't played Pete in a big match in a long time," Agassi, the
1992 champion, said. "You should see some fireworks out there --
I'm really looking forward to it."
</P>
<P>
It is the first all-American final since 1993 and pitches the
best grass-court player of his generation -- Sampras -- against
the most versatile shot-maker of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
In 23 matches they have played only once on grass, at Wimbledon
in 1993, a quarter-final match which gave Sampras one of his 13
victories in a rivalry going back to junior days.
</P>
<P>
"We have played consistently over the years and with our
different games and personalities, it's a great match-up. There's
a lot of respect we have for one another," said Sampras.
</P>
<P>
"I have to use the surface to my advantage and go out and play
some good tennis."
</P>
<P>
If he wins on Sunday Sampras will equal the record of 12 Grand
Slam titles held by Australian Roy Emerson.
</P>
<P>
Seven times champion Steffi Graf meets world number one Lindsay
Davenport of the U.S. in the women's final on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Graf came from a set down to claim a 6-7, 6-4, 6-3 win over 17-
year-old Croatian Mirjana Lucic on Saturday while Lindsay
Davenport ended the dream run of compatriot Alexandra Stevenson,
the first woman qualifier to reach the Wimbledon last four.
</P>
<P>
Davenport's clinical 6-1, 6-1 victory took her into her first
Wimbledon final and back to the top of the world rankings,
toppling Martina Hingis, the Swiss top seed beaten in the first
round here.
</P>
<P>
The final pitches the form player of the past six weeks, Graf,
who won the French Open last month, against the U.S. Open champion,
who has finally learned to love playing on grass.
</P>
<P>
They have played each other 13 times since 1994, with Graf
emerging victorious eight times. However, they have yet to meet
on a grass court and Davenport, 23, knows the 30-year-old Graf is
at her most dangerous at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
"Grass is Steffi's best surface and, along with Martina
Navratilova, she is one of the best grass-court players ever.
</P>
<P>
"You have to be aggressive against her on grass. You have to
hit the ball hard and keep it deep, and then do everything else
well," she said.
</P>
<P>
Davenport had never gone past the quarter-finals in six
previous visits to Wimbledon but she fears nobody after not losing
a set and conceding just 28 games in six rounds in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"It's going to be difficult to win, but I'm feeling great and
very relaxed. It will be a very exciting moment," she added.
</P>
<P>
Graf knows that one of her main weapons -- her serve -- will
have to improve in her ninth final at the All England Club.
</P>
<P>
She struggled in the first set against Lucic, losing her serve
four times. "I definitely have to serve better than I did against
Lucic.
</P>
<P>
"Like Mirjana, Davenport will go for her returns. She's going
to try and put the pressure on from the start, but if I can serve
well, I might be able to keep her on the move while she's serving.
"
</P>
<P>
If she beats Davenport, it will be Graf's 23rd Grand Slam
singles crown, putting her just one adrift of the record held by
Margaret Court.
</P>
<P>
After winning the French Open last month for the sixth time she
retired from the Roland Garros tournament. But Graf has said it
would be "tempting" to come back to Wimbledon next year if she
manages to capture her eighth title on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Such a situation would present her with a chance of equaling
Navratilova's record nine singles wins at Wimbledon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
