<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teenage Challenge Ends in Semis at Wimbledon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The last of the impressive young
teenagers at this year's Wimbledon have been beaten in the women's
semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
Alexandra Stevenson, 16, and 17-year-old Mirjana Lucic both
lost to their more experienced opponents.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Open champion Lindsay Davenport and seven times Wimbledon
winner Steffi Graf will now meet in the final.
</P>
<P>
But whereas Davenport breezed to a 6-1, 6-1 win over fellow
American Stevenson in 47 minutes, Graf had to come from a set down
against Lucic.
</P>
<P>
The score of 6-7 (3/7), 6-4, 6-3 reflected what a tough job the
German was given by the young talent from Croatia.
</P>
<P>
But Stevenson's attempt to become the first women's qualifier
to reach a Wimbledon final ended in tears on Center Court as
Davenport's power -- and the occasion -- overcame her. The
nervous teenager lost the first 11 points of the match.
</P>
<P>
And although she improved to force a number of Davenport
service games to deuce she could not break through.
</P>
<P>
The end came when Davenport produced a perfect love service
game and Stevenson sent a wild forehand way over the baseline.
</P>
<P>
The victory also ensures that older American replaces Martina
Hingis as world no 1.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards Davenport was relieved she had been able to grab the
initiative early in the match.
</P>
<P>
"She had been playing freely and loose, so I knew it was
important to get off to a good start," Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
"I think she was a little too excited and missed a lot of shots
she'd been making in the this tournament."
</P>
<P>
Graf remains on course for an eighth Wimbledon title but Lucic
produced some brilliant ground strokes to thrill the crowd on
Court One.
</P>
<P>
Graf raised her game in the second and third sets to claim the
win after losing the opener on a tie-break.
</P>
<P>
That set saw eight breaks of serve broken by Graf holding hers
on one occasion midway through the run.
</P>
<P>
Lucic recovered from a double fault on the first point of the
tie-break and took the next five points in a row and eventually
the set.
</P>
<P>
The second set went with serve until Lucic served to stay in
the set at 4-5.
</P>
<P>
She made an uncharacteristic basic error on set point, putting
a straightforward volley wide to allow Graf to draw level.
</P>
<P>
The momentum had swung firmly in the German's favor and she
made the crucial break in the second game of the deciding set by
forcing Lucic to volley into the net before putting a backhand
long.
</P>
<P>
Lucic kept fighting to the end but Graf's serve had improved
hugely since the opening set and yet another Wimbledon final
beckons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
