<HEADLINE> Hainan Promotes Aquatic Produce Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, July 4 (Xinhua) -- South China's Hainan Province
exported 35,000 tons of aquatic products in the first half of this
year, up 10.3 percent from the year-ago period of last year.
</P>
<P>
In addition to export growth in silver anchovies, sierra, and
prawns, some marine byproducts made by local processing
enterprises such as agar, fish mucus and alga were sold well in
Japan, the Republic of Korea, Taiwan and Macao.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the fresh aquatic products export
accounted for 20-25 percent of the province's total aquatic
products export. Baimajin fishing harbor alone exported 1,200 tons
of frozen fish chips to Japan in the first six months.
</P>
<P>
A local aquatic production official attributes the export
increase to last year's 11.7 percent increase in fishing
production and 993 hectares of production area added for the
aquatic industry in the province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
