<HEADLINE> Canada Getting Three New National Parks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Canada is getting three new national
parks this Summer in the country's far north new territory of
Nunavut, local media said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
After four years of talks, the Canadian cabinet and the Inuit
have ratified a deal on the establishment of three Arctic national
parks of Sirmilik, Auyuittug and Quttinirtaaq, adding 80,000
square kilometers of land to national parkland.
</P>
<P>
The Inuktitut names, meaning "place of glaciers," "land that
never melts," and "top of the world," were chosen to illustrate
the frozen terrain's major features, which are being described as
exotic northern gems.
</P>
<P>
"This is a way for the Inuit to connect with the rest of
Canada," said Paul Amagoalik, a chief Inuit negotiator of the
deal.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that "the parks will highlight things that
you can't find anywhere else in the world."
</P>
<P>
Canadian Heritage Minister Sheila Copps is scheduled to visit
Pond Inlet on Baffin Island in August for the official signing of
the agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
