<DOCNO> XIE19990704.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebuilding Aid Issue Worries Balkan Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Balkan countries
are concerned over the West's initial promises of substantial aid
for the whole of South-Eastern Europe since they believed that the
aid of reconstruction appeared to have been watered down.
</P>
<P>
The West has promised a huge new "Marshall Plan" of the aid for
Balkan reconstruction, but the sums are steadily shrinking while
the focus was being narrowed to Kosovo itself, according to a
twice-weekly European Report issued on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU)'s publication said that Leaders from
Macedonia, Albania, Bulgaria and Romania accused the West at a
meeting on Thursday of backsliding on its promises of aid to help
rebuild countries in South-Eastern Europe hurt by the Kosovo
conflict.
</P>
<P>
"There is fear that what has been promised will be prolonged to
an unspecified time. The stability pact is being delayed from
month to month," Macedonian Prime Minister Ljubco Georgievski said
at the Central and Eastern European economic summit. "Now we see
that it will come through only in September, then it may be pushed
into a new budgetary year," he said, adding "This is creating
dissatisfaction among us".
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the EU's executive arm, has said that
the cost of reconstruction in Kosovo and neighboring Balkan
countries is set to weigh down the entire EU budget procedure and
create tensions between the Council of Ministers and the European
Parliament, the other two arms of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, EU sources said finance ministers from the Group of
Seven (G7) industrialized countries and the major international
financial bodies, namely the International Monetary Fund, World
Bank, and European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, will
meet in Brussels on July 13 to discuss Balkans reconstruction.
They were said to prepare the ground for a donor conference at the
end of the month.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia, Albania, Bulgaria and Romania all suffered
economicly because of the NATO bombing against Yugoslavia.
Macedonia and Albania have hosted ethnic Kosovo Albanian refugees
since the airstrike started on March 24.
</P>
<P>
The Balkan leaders have call on foreign companies to take steps
as soon as possible to invest in the war-hit countries for
economic reconstruction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
